solutions.content:
# Observation 1- How to traverse
In this approach I have traversed the path of the spiral after making a few observations. If you refer 
Example 2, R = 5, C = 6, r0 = 1, c0 = 4, you will notice the direction of the walk does not change
from 1 to 2, 
2 to 3, 
3 to 5,
5 to 7, ....
Here  2-1 = 3-2
5-3 = 7-5
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/debipur/image_1579243848.png)
This brings us to our first observation, the length of the line along which direction does not change
remains equal after the odd number of changes and after even direction changes the length 
increases by 1.
# Approach
So, our approach here is we keep track of our current coordinates. Also have a array which stores the
change required to move right, down, left and up respectively :- {{0, 1}, {1, 0}, {0, -1}, {-1, 0}}.
According to the no. of steps taken, position in current line and no. of direction changes we make 
the change to our current cordinate. At each coordinate we check whether it is a valid cell, if so we 
push it to answer.
```
inline bool isvalid(vector<int> &cur, int R, int C){
	if(cur[0] >= 0 && cur[1] >= 0 && cur[0] < R && cur[1] < C)
		return true;
	return false;
}
```
# Observation 2- How long to traverse
The question is how long we need to move? If you draw(rather imagine) the spiral, for the following
boundary case it answers our question, R = 100, C = 1, r0 = 0, c0 = 0. You will find (2*max(R, C))^2 is
the maximum number of steps you will need.
```
vector<vector<int>> spiralMatrixIII(int R, int C, int r0, int c0) {
        vector<vector<int>> ans;
        vector<int> cur = {r0, c0};
        ans.push_back(cur);
        vector<vector<int>> dir = {{0, 1}, {1, 0}, {0, -1}, {-1, 0}};
        int totsteps = 2*max(R, C); totsteps*=totsteps;
		int stepi = 0, d = 0;                    //tracks i th step and d th direction change
        int linelen = 1;
        while(stepi <= totsteps){
            for(int a = 1; a <=2; ++a){          // looping twice for same length
                int k = 1;                       //tracks steps taken in current line
                while(k <= linelen){
                    cur[0] += dir[d][0];
                    cur[1] += dir[d][1];
                    if(isvalid(cur, R, C)) ans.push_back(cur);
                    k++; stepi++;
                }
                d = (d+1)%4;
            }
            linelen++;
        }
        return ans;
    }
```
