# Solution

Add start cell to the solution list. 

Start from given starting position and walk until result list contains all `R * C` cells.

# Complexity

Worst case scenario when $$R = 1$$, $$C > 1$$, and starting position $$(0, C-1)$$ corner. To reach $$(0, C-2)$$ we need to do spiral around, and trace $$3 *3$$ square before we reach starting position. To reach $$(0, C-3)$$ cell we must do $$5 * 5$$ moves. It is easy to see that the algorithm will require $$O(max(R, C)^2)$$ steps to walk all $$R*C$$ cells.

# Code

```
// define how to add pairs
template<typename T, typename K>
void operator +=(pair<T,K> &lhs, const pair<T,K> &rhs) {
    lhs.first += rhs.first;
    lhs.second += rhs.second;
}

class Solution {

public:
    vector<vector<int>> spiralMatrixIII(int rows, int cols, int rStart, int cStart) {

        pair<int, int> pos = { rStart, cStart};

        const vector<pair<int,int>> dirs = {
            {  0,  1 }, // E
            {  1,  0 }, // S
            {  0, -1 }, // W
            { -1,  0 }  // N
        };

        vector<vector<int>> ans;
        ans.reserve(rows*cols); // from problem statement
        ans.push_back({pos.first, pos.second});

        const int cnt = rows * cols;

        int r = 1; // radius
        int s = 0; // steps

        while (ans.size() < cnt) {
            const auto &move = dirs[s++ % dirs.size()];

            for (int k = 0; k < r && ans.size() < cnt; ++k) {
                pos += move;

                if (pos.first == clamp(pos.first, 0, rows - 1) && 
                    pos.second == clamp(pos.second, 0, cols - 1)) {
                    ans.push_back({pos.first, pos.second});
                }
            }

            // every two steps increase radius
            if (s % 2 == 0) {
                r++;
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
```

